	hr
	h4 Actor and Lisper: Shiro Kawai
	p Some website I looked at recently (probably looking something up about Emacs) using was built in Gauche Scheme, one of the distros I hadn't heard much about. The developer is named Shiro Kawai, which I thought was an interesting name#[+footnote "shiro" = white and "kawaii" = cute in Japanese, although it's probably something different for a name.].

	p The most interesting fact about him is that he is a professional programmer and actor. I don't really think I've seen many programmers do much else (#[a(href="https://data.typeracer.com/pit/text_info?id=3811095") relevant quote]), especially in the arts. What's more, he wrote #[a(href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=24096046") some papers] about how he uses Scheme in movie production. According to #[a(href="https://usesthis.com/interviews/shiro.kawai/") his interview on #[em Uses This]], he coding preference is Lisp (CL, Clojure, and Gauche of course) and these come up both in hobbyist and professional contexts. And he uses Emacs.

	p Seems like a really cool guy.

	hr
	h4 Org mode and project explorer for Emacs
	p These are two plugins I'd like to try.

	p #[a(href="https://orgmode.org/") Org mode] seems impressively popular. It's an Emacs package that provides a notetaking (Org-anization) major mode for Emacs. In the context in which I saw it (coming up later in this brain dump), it was being used to generate a website with its publish feature. It's large enough that they use the term #[a(href="https://orgmode.org/worg/") Worg] (World of Org). From a quick glance it seems like a plaintext markup language like Markdown, but with Emacs features like embedded code snippet "panes" (I'm not sure what the correct term would be). Seem like a high learning curve though, with the number of features it seems to offer.

	p Another thing I've been looking at is #[a(href="https://github.com/sabof/project-explorer") project-explorer] which does exactly what you think it does. I haven't tried this out either, but it looks very appealing as I'm not totally navigating buffers and windows#[+footnote What Emacs calls "windows," i.e., the panels that each contain a buffer in the Emacs editor. What I usually think of as a "window" Emacs calls a "frame."] in Emacs yet. My mode of navigation mostly comprises #[kbd C-x o] and #[kbd C-x b], which is really inefficient with more than three buffers (usually I'm cross-referencing many more files than that) or when a term-mode buffer is open (then the #[kbd C-x] prefixes become #[kbd C-c] prefixes].

