	h4 Words of Wisdom
	p Some terminology/techniques I learnt from work. I don't think any of these are proprietary so they can be shared here.
	ul
		li Sprint retrospective: A part of the Agile process. At the end of a sprint, do some meta reflection. Honestly, it feels very blunt and awkward, but if it works it works. (We actually did something similar in our club meetings for IEEExACM, but I didn't know it was called a retrospective.)
		li RCA (Root Cause Analysis): a formal method of problem solving used to address some issue (e.g., a workflow issue) to prevent it from happening again. Sounds like the STAR (Stop. Think. Act. Reflect.) method from high school wellness classes, and also extremely blunt.
		li code smell: from Wikipedia: "characteristic in the source code of a program that possibly indicates a deeper problem."
		li LCM (Launch Control Meeting): a meeting with the higher-ups to determine whether a new feature should be added shortly before a release. The closer the release or the larger the feature, the higher the risks (e.g., bugs).

	p Not from work, but some other terms I've recently acquired.
	ul
		li perspicuous: from Google (Oxford Languages) "(of an account or representation) clearly expressed and easily understood; lucid; (of a person) able to give an account or express an idea clearly." I am clearly not pespicuous in the second sense of the term, although I am always trying to get better.
		li tranclusion: the inclusion of one file into another by hypertext reference (think of a LaTeX #[code \input] command).
		li technical debt: from Wikipedia, "a concept in software development that reflects the implied cost of additional rework caused by choosing an easy (limited) solution now instead of using a better approach that would take longer." The analogy continues with the concept of "interest" if the technical debt remains unpaid.
		li opportunity cost: the cost of making one choice as opposed to the alternative. Even if the current choice doesn't incur any real cost, the alternative may give some benefit, which makes the chosen choice relative costly.

