	h4 A very similar website, by Yann Esposito
	p During one of my searches about Emacs and ViM, I stumbled across #[a(href='http://yannesposito.com/Scratch/en/blog/Learn-Vim-Progressively/') "Learn Vim Progressively"] by Yann Esposito. I wasn't really looking for that post, but I immediately noticed that the website had a very similar feel to mine. The centered, narrow column of text; the plain text and minimal styling; the consistent simple header and footer across pages -- it felt very similar to this site. Going back to the #[a(href="http://yannesposito.com/") homepage] of the site, there are also posts about how the site was (statically) generated. #[a(href="http://yannesposito.com/Scratch/en/blog/01_nanoc/") originally, it was built on the framework called nanoc]. #[a(href="http://yannesposito.com/posts/0001-new-blog/index.html") The newer edition is based on the Org mode publish tool] (this is how I encountered Org mode originally) and #[a(href="http://yannesposito.com/posts/0017-static-blog-builder/index.html") uses a Makefile to selectively build pages]#[+footnote In comparison, my very simple static website generator is probably much simpler than Org-publish, and I have yet to see how it would play with Makefiles due to its nested nature. But this is probably coming soon as the number of blog posts increases.].

	p In the last link, Yann puts forward some of the design guidelines for his website, which are basically a superset of mine. I was mostly focused on performance, readability, and consistency. Yann also proposes respecting privacy (no dependencies on external CSS/JS) and generates RSS (which I haven't done (yet)). He also describes his website as theme-switchable and frugal, and these also apply to my website even if they weren't conscious decisions.

	p The subject of some of the other blog posts include Haskell, Git, Vim, jQuery, so it seems like we have a lot in common! Like Shiro, it would be really cool to meet Yann.

